\begin_layout Abstract
The measure of agreement called
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 (i) We provide a new estimator the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 which is consistent, where Gwet's estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is merely an approximation.
 Moreover, this estimtor and has smaller variance than Gwet's estimator.
 (ii) Generalize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to different classes of guessing models.
 (iii) Argue that the weighted variant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is incorrectly defined, and provide an alternative.
 (iv) Question the motivation and utility of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and propose to use knowledge coefficients in its favour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Equation (17)"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 defines the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{p_{a}-p_{e}}{1-p_{e}}.\label{eq:Gwet correct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of chance agreement, defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p_a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of agreement due to chance in a particular sense, namely
 that the raters agree but at least of one of them is correct due to guessing.
 In the context of the guessing model, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{e}=p_{a}-\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}E[s_{ij}s_{ij'}]=p_{a}-\nu.\label{eq:pe}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 depends on knowing the skill parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

, it only makes sense only in a guessing model.
 From the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

, it follows that the numerator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}-p_{e}=\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}s_{j}s_{j'}=\nu$
\end_inset

, the skill coefficient.
 Thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{e}}=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{a}+\nu}.\label{eq:ac1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is estimable if the knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and the percent agreement 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is.
 The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{e}$
\end_inset

 has, as far as I can see, never been properly motivated, neither by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Chapter 4"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Gwet's explanations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 appear to match the skill coefficient much better, with the details narrowing
 it down to the Perrault–Leigh model, and the most appropriate coefficient
 for those persuaded by Gwet's arguments is the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be aware that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Chapter 4"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 redefines the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{\star}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{e}^{\star}}{1-p_{e}^{\star}},\quad\textrm{where }p_{e}^{\star}=\frac{1}{C-1}\sum_{c=1}^{C}p(c)(1-p(c))=\frac{1-p_{ca}}{C-1}\label{eq:AC1 approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Originally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "eq. 22"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presented 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

 as an approximation to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, not the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient itself.
 In this paper we will understand 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient, not the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}-p_{e}=\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}s_{j}s_{j'}$
\end_inset

 and the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}=\binom{J}{2}^{-1}s_{j}s_{j'}(1-p_{ga})+p_{ga}$
\end_inset

, we find that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p_{e} & = & p_{a}-\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}s_{j}s_{j'}=\frac{1-p_{a}}{p_{ga}^{-1}-1},\label{eq:pe (Gwet model)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

It follows that the generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ga}$
\end_inset

 only, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=\frac{p_{a}-p_{e}}{1-p_{e}}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{ga}}{1-2p_{ga}+p_{a}g_{ga}}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{ga}}{1-p_{ga}(2-p_{a})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the plug-in estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\gamma}=\frac{\hat{p}_{ga}^{-1}\hat{p}_{a}-1}{\hat{p}_{ga}^{-1}-2+\hat{p}_{a}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the empirical agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sample
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 has simple asymptotics under the Brennan–Prediger model.
 Using the delta method, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(\hat{\gamma}-\gamma)$
\end_inset

 converges in distribution to a normal with standard deviation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sd(\gamma)=\sqrt{p_{2a}-p_{a}^{2}}\frac{(C-1)^{2}}{(C+p_{a}-2)^{2}}.\label{eq:AC1 plugin standard deviation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this expression to construct approximate confidence intervals.
 It is possible, but rare, even for small 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{2a}<\hat{p}_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 as an estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2a}-p_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gwet's estimator of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is the plugin estimator based on the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}=(p_{a}-p_{e}^{\star})/(1-p_{e}^{\star})$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AC1 approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{e}^{\star} & = & (C-1)^{-1}\sum_{x=1}^{C}p(x)(1-p(x))=\frac{1-p_{ca}}{C-1}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The correct is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}=\frac{1-p_{a}}{C-1}$
\end_inset

, however.
 This estimator is almost always inconsistent, even under the BP model,
 but the bias is quite small.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:coverage ac1"

\end_inset

An illustration 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the BP model, i.e.
 a guessing model where the guessing distribution is uniform.
 We will compare the coverage of normal theory confidence interval derived
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AC1 plugin standard deviation-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, using the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom and , to the confidence interval described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The true distribution of ratings is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.1,0.05,0.65,0.1,0.2)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

