\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 under different assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inference for the van Oest-type 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is somewhat more involved than for the ordinary 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient, as its expression involves 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}$
\end_inset

 in addition to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{a},p_{ca})$
\end_inset

 is complicated, precluding the use of the delta method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The knowledge coefficient vs the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We believe that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is poorly motivated as a measure of agreement, both under the BP model
 and the Fleiss model.
 Indeed, we believe the correct measure of agreement is the skill coefficient
 in both cases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the skill coefficient can be interpreted in more than one way.
 Flei
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
On the weighted 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, also known as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

 coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already argued that 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not properly motived, but at least it is better motivated than its weighted
 variant, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{a}(w)-p_{e}^{\star}(w)}{1-p_{e}^{\star}(w)},\quad\textrm{where }p_{e}^{\star}(w)=\frac{1-p_{ca}}{C-1}\frac{\sum_{x,y}w(x,y)}{C}.
\]

\end_inset

The motivation behind 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}^{\star}(w)$
\end_inset

 is hard to follow, possibly because it is based directly on the approximation
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 instead of the correct 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that (i) the raters agree and (ii) that at least of
 one of them is correct due to guessing.
 To make a weighted variant of this quantity, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 can be understood as the percent agreement minus the probability that the
 agreement is due to the judges knowing the correct classification.
 When making a weighted variant of this, the only the percent agreement
 is affected, yielding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{e}(w)=p_{a}(w)-\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}s_{j}s_{j'}=p_{a}(w)-\nu.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 weighted 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(w)=\frac{p_{a}(w)-p_{e}(w)}{1-p_{e}(w)}=\frac{\nu}{\nu+1-p_{a}(w)}.
\]

\end_inset

A natural estimator would use the sample Brennan–Prediger coefficient (sample
 Fleiss' kappa) in the BP model (Fleiss model) to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}(w)$
\end_inset

 using the sample weighted agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As is the case with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, we believe dividing the skill coefficient with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu+1-p_{a}(w)$
\end_inset

 is unjustified, and would recommend sticking with skill coefficients such
 as the Brennan–Prediger coefficient or Fleiss' kappa.
\end_layout

